VERDICT: REJECTED
The admin panel implementation is not ready to mark complete because it introduces a blocking data-integrity bug and a serious access-control risk.

Critical findings:
1) The “delete all” endpoints use bulk ORM deletion on parent tables, which bypasses relationship cascades. In practice, deleting all courses/books leaves related child rows (modules/quizzes/assignments/activities) orphaned in the database. This means data is not actually cleaned up and can accumulate inconsistent records; with stricter FK enforcement this pattern can fail outright.
2) All admin routes are publicly accessible with no authentication/authorization guard, while exposing full settings (including API-key-like values) and destructive operations (single/bulk deletes). For an admin surface, this is a direct broken-access-control issue.

Security: serious violation observed — missing authz on privileged admin endpoints, enabling unauthorized settings/API key access and destructive writes.

Next actions:
1) Fix delete-all logic to preserve referential integrity (delete through ORM instances so cascades execute, or explicitly delete dependent rows in a transaction before parent deletion).
2) Add protection middleware/check for all `/admin` routes and APIs (at minimum session-based password gate) before exposing settings and destructive actions.
3) Add targeted tests for admin auth enforcement and for parent/child deletion behavior to prevent regression.

